<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   British Combat Software Selected for Destroyers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    British Combat Software Selected for Destroyers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1305035194 Seoul YONHAP in English 0253 GMT 13 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1305035194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, May 13 (YONHAP) -- The Defense Ministry gave 
final approval Friday to the Navy's choice of a British combat 
system for Korea's new destroyers. 
  The final contract saved Korea 22 billion won as the price 
of 
the SSCS (Surface Ship Combat System)-MK7 was cut 34 percent 
from the original offer in 1992 and revised to minimize treasury 
loss on the part of Korea, ministry officials said. 
  The advanced software system of Bae-Sema Ltd. (BSL), to be 
installed in the new warships under the KDX (Korean Destroyer 
Project) program, was selected over Germany's Cosys-200K1. 
  The Defense Ministry completely revised the screening 
process 
for the combat system when the German equipment was chosen in 
June last year despite the Navy's preference for the British 
version. 
  The fact that the British Navy already has a contract on a 
similar destroyer system that the Koreans wish to adopt and that 
the British system was estimated to have better "follow-up 
logistics support" tilted Korea toward the SSCS, the officials 
said. 
  The SSCS sets will be installed in the next-generation Navy 
destroyers, now under construction, with advanced computer 
operational capability.The project is due to be completed by 
1998. 

</TEXT>

