<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reformers Object to President, Buddhist Meeting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reformers Object to President, Buddhist Meeting </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1305110494 Seoul YONHAP in English 1052 GMT 13 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1305110494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, May 13 (YONHAP) -- A planned meeting between 
President Kim Yong-sam and Buddhist leaders was called off on 
Friday due to objection by some reformist Buddhist leaders. 
  The Culture and Sports Ministry had arranged the meeting as 
part of the administrative move to mend discords between the 
administration and the Buddhist circles caused by the recent 
Chogye-sa incident. 
  "We had prepared for a meeting between President Kim and the 
Rev. Wolha, the new Chogye order patriarch, and other Chogye 
leaders at the suggestion of the Culture-Sports Ministry, but it 
failed to take place due to objection by some reformist 
leaders," a Chongwadae [presidential offices] official said. 
  He said Chongwadae planned to hold the meeting on next 
Monday, two days before the Buddha's coming day, Wednesday. 
  "But, some reformist Chogye leaders demanded that prior to 
the meeting, President Kim should make an apology and Home 
Minister Choe Hyong-u resign in connection with the violence at 
the Chogye temple," he said. 
  The official hinted that the administration would try to 
realize the meeting again once the inhouse situation of the 
Chogye order is put to an order. 
  Noting that dialogue is going on with Buddhist leaders in 
various channels, the official said that when an atmosphere is 
fostered through a dialogue, Buddhist leaders' meeting with the 
president will be materialized as a matter of course. 

</TEXT>

