<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-53347 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas095_d_94027" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-095 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  8 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pardons During National Holidays Discontinued </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Pardons During National Holidays Discontinued </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0805061694 Seoul YONHAP in English 0551 GMT 8 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0805061694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, May 8 (YONHAP) -- There will be no special 
pardon for imprisoned criminals this year in commemoration of 
Buddha's birthday next week, the Justice Ministry said Sunday. 
The government will minimize the number of felons released from 
special amnesty granted during national holidays every year and 
refer the convicted criminals to the regular release on the 20th 
of every month, the Ministry said. 
  Ministry officials said the change is due to rising number 
of 
repeat offenses by those who have been released on holiday 
amnesty. There was also concern that the release of security law 
violators was weakening the seriousness of the law, they said. 
  Special holiday amnesty released approximately 100 more 
criminals than during monthly pardon. The change in government 
release is expected to reduce the number of pardoned criminals 
by 400 to 500 a year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

