<H3> <TI>   Ruling Party Names New Party Spokesman </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ruling Party Names New Party Spokesman </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0705035594 Seoul YONHAP in English 0251 GMT 7 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0705035594 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, May 7 (YONHAP) -- The ruling Democratic 
Liberal Party appointed Rep. Pak Pom-chin as its new spokesman 
on Saturday. 
  The party accepted resignations handed in by Spokesman Ha 
Sun-pong and three deputy spokesmen -- Cho Yong-chik, O 
Chang-sop and Son Hak-kyu earlier in the day. 
  New deputy spokesmen are expected to be named on Monday. 
  Explaining the background of the change, DLP 
Secretary-General Mun Chong-su said, "Spokesman Ha expressed his 
intention to resign and the party accepted the resignations of 
Ha and the three deputy spokesmen to change the atmosphere in 
the spokesman's office." 
  Ha reportedly resigned assuming responsibility for the 
tension between the DLP and the Democratic Party created by his 
recent remarks that retired opposition leader Kim Tae-chung had 
covertly encouraged the opposition Democratic Party to adopt a 
hard-line stance toward the ruling party. 
  New DLP Spokesman Pak, 54, was born in Chechon-kun, North 
Chungchong Province, and graduated from the political science 
department at Seoul National University. He worked at the 
CHOSON ILBO and served as editorial writer for the SEOUL SINMUN. 

</TEXT>

