<H3> <TI>   Kwangju Uprising Victims To File Legal Complaint </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kwangju Uprising Victims To File Legal Complaint </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1205090694 Seoul YONHAP in English 0722 GMT 12 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1205090694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kwangju, May 12 (YONHAP) -- Coinciding with the 14th 
anniversary of the "Kwangju civil uprising," a local group of 
victims of the bloody government suppression announced Thursday 
it would lodge a criminal complaint against former Presidents 
Chon Tu-hwan and No Tae-u and 33 others for alleged treason and 
homicide. 
  "Ominnyon" told a news conference it would file the 
complaint 
with the Seoul district prosecutor's office Friday, adding that 
321 victims of the May 18 civil uprising will be plaintiffs in 
the complaint. 
  "We decided to file the complaint against the 35 people 
because we considered it impossible to achieve true 
democratization and harmony in the country, as well as cherish 
the spirit of the May 18 civil uprising, without eliminating 
those forces who want to dilute the spirit of the uprising to 
maintain their vested interests," said an organization spokesman. 
  "The Kim Yong-sam government cannot achieve true reform 
unless it brings to light the true picture of the massacre 
during the uprising and takes judicial action against those 
responsible for the massacre," said the spokesman, criticizing a 
situation in which the victims themselves must take legal 
action. In the meantime, an organization of bereaved families 
of the uprising's victims said in a statement that the 
anniversary should become a national event, fostering a mood in 
which President Kim and government officials could visit 
Mangwoldong cemetery where those killed in the Kwangju civil 
uprising are buried. 

</TEXT>

