<H3> <TI>   Red Cross Proposes N-S Talks for Family Reunions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Red Cross Proposes N-S Talks for Family Reunions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0905014394 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 0100 GMT 9 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK0905014394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On 9 May, Kang Yong-hun, president of the ROK 
National Red Cross, proposed resuming North-South Red Cross 
talks to North Korea to exchange visiting groups of separated 
families and elderly parents and resolve the overall separated 
families issues. 
  President Kang Yong-hun asked the North Korean authorities 
to 
return approximately 400 persons who had been detained in North 
Korea, including the crew of the Tongjin boat and those of 
civilian airplanes, to their families' embraces. He proposed 
this during a speech to today's meeting marking the Day of 
International Red Cross. 
  He also said that reuniting members of separated families is 
a moral issue that transcends differences in ideology and 
systems and is a central point of humanitarianism. He also said 
that the North and South Red Cross Societies must start 
consultations on this matter as soon as possible. 
  President Kang Yong-hun also said that Ham Se-hwan and Kim 
In-so, whom North Korea had asked the ROK to return, are not 
POW's but ROK citizens. He also said that demanding their 
repatriation is not in compliance with Red Cross humanitarianism. 

</TEXT>

