Daily Report 
<DATE1>  11 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Socialist International Meets in Tokyo 11 May </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Socialist International Meets in Tokyo 11 May </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1105090194 Tokyo KYODO in English 0824 GMT 11 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1105090194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 11 KYODO -- Socialist, social democratic 
and labor parties from all over the world meeting at a congress 
in Tokyo advocated Wednesday [11 May] that Japan and Germany 
become permanent members of an enlarged U.N. Security Council. 
  "The Socialist International supports an increase in the 
number of permanent members to include Germany and Japan as well 
as a number of regional representatives, whilst ensuring that 
the developing world is properly represented," representatives 
from 63 parties and organizations said in a resolution. 
  The Socialist International (SI) currently comprises 111 
political parties and organizations worldwide. 
  Summing up the two-day congress at a news conference the SI 
president, former French Prime Minister Pierre Mauroy, noted 
that the Tokyo meeting aimed at listening to the concerns of 
Asian countries and at strengthening the socialist movement 
globally. 
  Cambodian Second Prime Minister Hun Sen and representatives 
from Bangladesh, Myanmar [Burma], Cambodia, Laos and India were 
among the special guests at the congress which focused on 
democracy and social development in the Asia-Pacific region. 
  Mauroy said the SI, given the rapid economic development in 
the Asia-Pacific, must expand relations with free labor unions 
to counter the excesses of "wild capitalism" and protect Asian 
workers from the "great misery" that Europe experienced during 
the industrialization in the 19th century. 
  Speaking at the same news conference, the former head of the 
Social Democratic Party (SDP) of Japan, Makoto Tanabe, who is SI 
vice president, pointed to the congress resolution on Asia, 
which singles out North Korea as a security risk for its 
suspected nuclear weapons program. 
  "North Korea, which is defying the demand of the U.N. that 
it 
implement comprehensive safeguards measures, can never gain the 
support of the international community," the resolution said. 
  The SDP has long maintained friendly relations with North 
Korea. However, Tanabe said, "on these issues we express, of 
course, our agreement to this resolution." 
  Tanabe called on Pyongyang to allow inspections by the 
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) and on other countries 
to intensify efforts to dissuade North Korea from developing 
nuclear weapons. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-53383 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas097aa_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-097 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  30 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   PRC Joins Association of Tin Producing Countries </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PRC Joins Association of Tin Producing Countries </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK0105131894 Bangkok ZHONG HUA RIBAO in Chinese 30 Apr 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> BK0105131894 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok ZHONG HUA RIBAO </F>
<F P=105>  Chinese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] At 1100 on 29 April, Sukhum Ratsamithat, director 
general of the Foreign Ministry's Economic Affairs Department, 
presided over the signing of an agreement at the Foreign 
Ministry under which China joined the Association of Tin 
Producing Countries. Chinese Ambassador to Thailand Jin Guihua 
signed the agreement establishing the Association of Tin 
Producing Countries on behalf of the Chinese Government. Also 
present at the signing ceremony were Indonesian and Malaysian 
representatives and officials from the Mineral Resources 
Department and the Foreign Ministry. 
  The signing ceremony took place in Thailand because the Thai 
Foreign Ministry is the depository of the agreement. The 
Association's membership increases from seven to eight with 
China's accession. The other seven members of the Association 
are Australia, Bolivia, Indonesia, Malaysia, Nigeria, Zaire, and 
Thailand. All of these countries have joined the Association 
since 1983. 
  The Foreign Ministry pointed out that it is good that China 
has joined the Association. Previously, China was only an 
observer of the Association even though it is the largest tin 
producer. China's membership will strengthen the Association's 
position and bargaining power in talks with tin consuming 
countries to solve problems with tin oversupply and falling tin 
prices jointly. 
  The establishment of the Association of Tin Producing 
Countries was aimed at ensuring fair tin prices and supplies and 
enhancing cooperation in tin marketing and tin resources 
research and development. 
  The Association also agreed upon three conditions for China 
to join the Association: 
  1. China will report its tin exports to the Association 
every quarter. 
  2. China will pay a membership fee in proportion to its 
tin exports. 
  3. China will temporarily not be invited to join the 
International Tin Research Association. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

