Daily Report 
<DATE1>  19 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Intent To `Intimidate' Condemned </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Intent To `Intimidate' Condemned </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1905055094 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0520 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1905055094 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Dangerous Scheme" -- KCNA headline] </F>
  [Text] Pyongyang, May 19 (KCNA) -- U.S. Secretary of 
Defense William Perry recently declared the United States was 
examining measures to step up preparations for an emergency 
dispatch of aircraft carriers to the Korean peninsula and 
increase the stockpile of ammunitions for U.S. Forces in South 
Korea and Japan. A senior U.S. official even cried that a 
"decisive position" would be taken in the U.S.-led international 
action for a solution to the "nuclear issue" of the DPRK. 
  This shows the United States is very tenaciously working to 
intimidate the Korean people with strength and strangle the 
DPRK, says NODONG SINMUN today. 
  The news analyst continues: 
  The emergency dispatch of aircraft carriers and stockpiling 
of larger quantities of ammunitions are measures that can be 
taken only on the eve of war. Perry's statement suggests that 
the United States is stepping up preparations for making a 
military adventure against the DPRK any moment. 
  It is noteworthy that the United States is intensifying the 
campaign to stifle the DPRK by force of arms over its "nuclear 
issue." 
  The United States is leading the campaign of international 
reactionaries to isolate and stifle the DPRK. This indicates 
that the U.S. schemes to inveigle other countries in a possible 
war it would provoke in Korea. 
  The U.S. is raising a hue and cry over the "nuclear issue" 
of 
the DPRK in an effort to find a pretext for a military adventure. 
  Strength and pressure never work on the DPRK. 
  If the U.S. warmaniacs make a military adventure in Korea, 
they will have to pay dearly for it. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

