<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Anniversary of 1980 Kwangju Incident Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Anniversary of 1980 Kwangju Incident Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Hanminjon Issues Statement </H4>

<F P=102> SK1805105394 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1023 GMT 18 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1805105394 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, May 18 (KCNA) -- "We will fight, holding 
ever higher the banner of independence, democracy and 
reunification held aloft by the patriotic martyrs, undauntedly 
facing brutal suppression by the U.S. imperialists and the Kim 
Yong-sam clique and thereby overthrow the colonial fascist rule 
of the U.S. imperialists and establish an independent government 
of the nation in order not to spoil the price of blood shed by 
the valiant fighters of the Kwangju resistance," declared Cho 
Il-min, chief of the Pyongyang Mission of the South Korean 
National Democratic Front (Hanminjon), in a statement issued on 
Tuesday on the 14th anniversary of the Kwangju popular uprising. 
  "The uprising made the South Korean people clearly see that 
the United States is an aggressor and murderer, not a friend," 
he said. "Unless the Americans are driven away, the South Korean 
people cannot get rid of colonial slavery nor can achieve the 
democratisation of society and the independent, peaceful 
reunification of the country." 
  Cho Il-min further said: 
  "We will wage the anti-U.S., anti-fascist struggle more 
courageously, never forgetting the heinous crimes committed by 
the U.S. imperialist aggressors and the military fascist 
murderers in slaying in cold blood Kwangju citizens who 
courageously rose in the uprising for independence, democracy 
and reunification and turning Kwangju into a blood. 
  "The United States must take steps to pull its forces and 
nuclear weapons out of South Korea, clearly seeing that there is 
no room for it to stay in South Korea where anti-U.S. sentiments 
are growing day by day and not making light of the unshakable 
will of the South Korean people to fight it out to defend the 
national sovereignty. 
  "The United States must renounce its policy of isolating and 
stifling the DPRK over the `nuclear issue', sincerely seek a 
peaceful solution to the nuclear issue of the Korean peninsula 
through the medium of DPRK-USA negotiations and respond to the 
just proposal of the DPRK to replace the armistice agreement 
with a peace agreement." 

</TEXT>

