<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Red Cross Again Demands Return of Old POW's </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Red Cross Again Demands Return of Old POW's </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    KCNA Quotes Message </H4>

<F P=102> SK1905051994 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0449 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1905051994 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, May 19 (KCNA) -- Yi Song-ho, acting 
chairman of the Central Committee of the DPRK Red Cross Society, 
in a telephone message to the president of the South Korean Red 
Cross today, strongly urged the South side once again to show an 
affirmative response to the North's humanitarian proposals 
before it is too late. 
  Noting that the South side has not shown any response to the 
North's proposals for the repatriation to the North of Kim In-so 
and Ham Se-hwan, prisoners of war now under detention in South 
Korea, and of Kim Chi-hyon, a daughter of Kim Pyong-chu who was 
an unconverted prisoner, now suffering from a serious illness, 
the message says: 
  This cannot be deemed a righteous behavior of the Red Cross 
men whose essential mission is to show noble humanitarianism by 
saving human beings from misfortunes and helping them. 
  Kim In-so and Ham Se-hwan who were taken prisoners by the 
U.S. Forces side while engaging in guerrilla activities in the 
South Korean area during the Korean war are obviously prisoners 
of war in view of the international law, and your side is 
obliged to send them back to our side. 
  This notwithstanding, your side is dealing with their issue 
according to the "National Security Law" of South Korea which is 
now being denounced by the international community. This is, 
indeed, a wrong act of interpreting and applying the 
international law in a self-centred way. 
  Moreover, your side is behaving as if it were interested in 
humanitarian issues, while disregarding the question of 
repatriation of Kim In-so and Ham Se-hwan, a more urgent matter 
than the problem of separated families. This is an extremely 
improper act. 
  Failing to manifest any intention to give medical assistance 
to Kim Chi-hyon now in a critical condition, your side turned 
down our offer to fetch and treat her here. This cannot be 
construed otherwise than an attitude of neglecting the duty and 
mission of the Red Cross men. 
  The Central Committee of the DPRK Red Cross Society 
sincerely 
advises your organization not to follow the South side's 
authorities who pursue North-South confrontation but to remain 
faithful to its duty as a Red Cross organization. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

