<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Tokyo, Washington Framework Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Tokyo, Washington Framework Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Talks Resume 19 May </H4>

<F P=102> OW1905140594 Tokyo KYODO in English 1321 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1905140594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Antonio Kamiya] </F>
  [Text] Washington, May 19 KYODO -- Japan and the United 
States began an exploratory round of trade talks Thursday [19 
May] aimed at breaking a three-month deadlock on how to widen 
foreign access to the Japanese market and reducing Japan's vast 
trade surplus. 
  The meeting came amid fresh government data that showed the 
U.S. trade deficit with Japan jumped 25.4 percent in March to 
5.80 billion dollars. The U.S. posted a record 59 billion 
dollar deficit with Japan last year. 
  Both Japanese and U.S. officials were cautious in predicting 
the outcome of the day's trade meeting at the Office of the U.S. 
Trade Representative. 
  "We will not know anything until we meet," said Sozaburo 
Okamatsu, Japan's vice trade minister for international affairs. 
  Okamatsu made the brief remark to reporters as he and 
Sadayuki Hayashi, deputy foreign minister for economic affairs, 
entered the office. 
  The Americans sounded equally cautious. 
  "We will have to wait and see what the Japanese officials 
bring," a senior U.S. official told reporters on condition of 
anonymity Wednesday. 
  At stake is the fate of the accord the two countries 
concluded in July last year to set up a new framework for 
bilateral trade designed to widen the access of foreign goods to 
Japan and reduce Japan's global trade surplus. 
  Negotiations on how to implement the terms of the framework 
agreement broke down in February when Japan refused to accept 
the U.S. definition on "objective criteria" for measuring 
Japanese imports. 
  The rupture of the trade negotiations, which came at the 
Feb. 
11 summit in Washington between President Bill Clinton and then 
Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa, shook financial markets and at 
one point sent the U.S. dollar close to a record low against 
the yen. 
  Clinton and other senior U.S. officials have since made what 
appeared to be conciliatory remarks on bilateral trade ties, but 
officials in Tokyo say they are uncertain about Washington's 
intentions. 
  U.S. Trade Representative Mickey Kantor told reporters 
during a visit to Congress on Wednesday that the U.S. has not 
budged. 
  "Our position is exactly as it was in February. It has not 
changed at all," Kantor said. 
  Treasury Undersecretary for International Affairs Lawrence 
Summers, a member of the U.S. team involved in the trade talks 
with Japan, also insisted that the U.S. has not changed its 
position. 
  "I think (our) position has been consistent," Summers said 
in 
a separate meeting with reporters. 
  But Summers conceded that Washington will keep an eye on the 
shaky political situation in Tokyo when U.S. officials sit at 
the negotiating table with Japanese officials. 
  "Clearly, as we go forward in the negotiations, we have to 
recognize the political situation in Japan, and that obviously 
is one of the factors that goes into the strategy," he said. 
  While both Tokyo and Washington seem eager to get the 
framework talks back on track by the time Prime Minister Tsutomu 
Hata meets Clinton at the Group of Seven (G-7) summit of 
industrialized nations in Italy in early July, U.S. officials 
say there is no deadline for a deal. 
  "We are not putting any artificial deadline on them. We 
think that would be a mistake," a senior U.S. trade official 
said. 

</TEXT>

