<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Commission Charges Country With Dumping </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Commission Charges Country With Dumping </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Nippon Steel Regrets U.S. Charges </H4>

<F P=102> OW1905041094 Tokyo KYODO in English 0218 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1905041094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 19 KYODO -- Nippon Steel Corp. expressed 
regret Thursday [19 May] at a U.S. International Trade 
Commission ruling that Japanese steelmakers are selling certain 
steel products in the U.S. market at unfairly low prices. 
  "It's regrettable that our argument was not understood, but 
this is the ITC's final ruling, so we'll consider what to do in 
the future by considering the implications of it," a Nippon 
Steel official said. 
  At stake in the ruling are two types of special steel -- 
grain- oriented steel and stainless angle used in heavy 
electrical machinery and the construction industry. 

</TEXT>

