<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Commission Charges Country With Dumping </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Commission Charges Country With Dumping </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Steelmakers May Appeal </H4>

<F P=102> OW1905060394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0409 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1905060394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 19 KYODO -- Nippon Steel Corp. and 
Kawasaki Steel Corp. may file an appeal with the U.S. Court of 
International Trade, complaining that they have caused no damage 
to the steel market in the United States, officials of the 
companies said Thursday [19 May]. 
  Such a move would be in response to a ruling by the U.S. 
International Trade Commission (ITC) that the Japanese 
steelmakers are selling certain steel products in the U.S. at 
unfairly low prices. 
  A Nippon Steel official said, "Our company has shipped only 
special steel which is not manufactured by U.S. makers. The 
ITC's final decision is beyond our understanding." 
  Kawasaki Steel said ITC's decision will damage U.S. 
companies 
which have steadily imported steel products from Japan. 
  The company commented that if such unreasonable antidumping 
actions are frequently taken, it will damage the mutual goal of 
maintaining long-term global stability in steel trade. 

</TEXT>

