<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Japanese Bank To Suspend Dollar Payment to DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Japanese Bank To Suspend Dollar Payment to DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Kumagai Confirms Remittance Halt </H4>

<F P=102> OW1905090494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0850 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1905090494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 19 KYODO -- Chief Cabinet Secretary 
Hiroshi Kumagai said Thursday [19 May] Japanese banks have 
suspended remittances of dollars to North Korea, but he denied 
suggestions the move was in response to pressure from the 
government. The government understands that the banks decided 
to suspend the remittances for operational reasons, he said. 
  The United States urged Japan last month to regulate the 
flow 
of hard currencies to North Korea, which is suspected of using 
the funds to promote a clandestine nuclear weapons program. 
  It is not known how much money is remitted to North Korea 
from Japan, but trade and banking sources estimate the sum at 60 
billion yen a year, including trade bills. 
  Vice Finance Minister Jiro Saito denied at a scheduled 
evening press meeting that his ministry gave any instructions to 
Ashikaga Bank to stop the remittances. 
  Asked if he has confirmed that with the bank, Saito said the 
ministry's Banking Bureau had no idea about it when he contacted 
the bureau, and added that he has not heard anything further. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

