<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Urged To Act Over Rights in Burma </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Urged To Act Over Rights in Burma </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1805121594 Tokyo KYODO in English 1200 GMT 18 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1805121594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 18 KYODO -- A group of more than 500 
Japanese lawmakers urged the government of Prime Minister 
Tsutomu Hata on Wednesday [18 May] to help protect the human 
rights of people in Myanmar [Burma] and establish civilian rule 
in the country. 
  House of Representatives member Shokei Arai told a news 
conference he visited Chief Cabinet Secretary Hiroshi Kumagai at 
the premier's official residence and handed him a copy of a 
petition signed by 508 Japanese legislators. 
  The letter calls for the "immediate and unconditional 
release" of Myanmar's opposition leader Aung San Suu Kyi and all 
political prisoners in Myanmar as well as a "swift and complete 
implementation of a transition to civilian rule." 
  While noting that Tokyo has been demanding the release of 
the 
Nobel Peace prize laureate, Kumagai reportedly vowed greater 
efforts to make Myanmar become a democratic nation. 
  Arai, a member of the new party Jiyuto (Liberals) headed by 
Foreign Minister Koji Kaikzawa, said he and his associates plan 
to send the petition to U.N. Secretary General Butrus 
Butrus-Ghali, if possible by late July, when Suu Kyi was 
originally expected to be released from house arrest. 
  It will be the second such letter by Japanese politicians to 
the U.N. chief, following one by 374 Diet members sent to 
Butrus-Ghali in March 1993. 
  Last April, 422 Diet members urged the government to put 
pressure on Myanmar to release Suu Kyi. 
  A founder of the National League for Democracy (NLD) which 
won the 1990 general election by a landslide, Suu Kyi has been 
under house arrest since July 1989. 
  She was expected to be freed July 19 this year from her 
five-year detention, the maximum period allowed under law. 
  But in February the ruling junta, which refused to hand over 
power five years ago, said it regards the first year of her 
detention as an "arrest period" and full detention was not 
imposed until July 1990. She is now expected to be freed in 
July 1995. 

</TEXT>

