<H4>    Hata Orders Freeze on Service Charges </H4>

<F P=102> OW1805095694 Tokyo KYODO in English 0827 GMT 18 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1805095694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 18 KYODO -- Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata 
on Wednesday [18 May] instructed his aides to freeze the hikes 
in public service charges until the end of the year, Chief 
Cabinet Secretary Hiroshi Kumagai said. 
  The planned move is intended to stem the rate increases in 
domestic telephone charges, the rent for public housing, taxi 
fares, tolls for the nation's expressways and fire insurance 
premiums, the top government spokesman told a news conference. 
  The government will also ask local autonomies to refrain 
from 
raising fees charged for their bus and subway services, Kumagai 
said. 
  The premier ordered Kumagai and Economic Planning Agency 
Director General Yoshio Terasawa on Tuesday to move quickly to 
carry out the measure. 
  The cabinet will approve the scheme at its regular meeting 
on 
Friday, according to Kumagai. 

</TEXT>

