<H3> <TI>   Reactions to Hikes in Public Utility Charges Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reactions to Hikes in Public Utility Charges Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    MITI Vice Minister Praises Freeze </H4>

<F P=102> OW1905084094 Tokyo KYODO in English 0654 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1905084094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 19 KYODO -- Hideaki Kumano, vice 
minister of international trade and industry, said Thursday [19 
May] the government's decision to freeze hikes on public service 
fees is "appropriate." 
  The decision was made taking into account various factors 
facing the private sector, including business restructuring 
efforts, Kumano told a news conference. 
  Implementation of the rate hikes at a time when the economy 
is still in a slump would affect industrial activity in Japan, 
Kumano said. 
  The government announced Wednesday it will suspend until the 
end of this year a plan to raise public services charges, 
including public transportation fees, highway tolls, telephone 
rates and rent on government-owned houses. 
  Meanwhile, Kumano voiced regret over gasoline sales by an 
unlicensed gas station near Nagoya in defiance of government 
instructions. The gas station should get a government permit at 
an early time by agreeing to undergo proper procedures, Kumano 
said. 
  The gas station in question on Wednesday began selling 
gasoline at prices very low for Japan, and motorists flocked to 
fill up. The Ministry of International Trade and Industry did 
not issue a business license for the station because it did not 
clarify the wholesale routes of its products, one requirement 
for operating a gas station. A government advisory panel is now 
studying whether or not the requirement should be scrapped as 
part of deregulation, Kumano said. 

</TEXT>

