<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reactions to Hikes in Public Utility Charges Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reactions to Hikes in Public Utility Charges Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Press Welcomes Hata's Decision </H4>

<F P=102> OW1905063594 Tokyo KYODO in English 0556 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1905063594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 19 KYODO -- Leading Japanese newspapers 
in their editorials Thursday [19 May] supported Prime Minister 
Tsutomu Hata's freezing of the planned hikes in public service 
charges until the end of the year. The NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 
called the government 's decision "a natural measure." The 
business daily said it welcomes the decision because "raising 
public service charges has the same effect as raising taxes, and 
the government is facing a necessity to reduce taxes to promote 
consumption and get over the recession." It also said the 
recent rush of planned hikes in public service rates seems to 
have been done easily without satisfactory explanation, taking 
advantage of the disorder in the government to hoodwink the 
public. It called on public utilities to take rationalization 
measures as private companies do, and to disclose their business 
structures and try to obtain public understanding when they plan 
to increase charges. 
  The ASAHI SHIMBUN also said the decision to shelve the 
planned increase in public service charges is natural, although 
it was abrupt. The ASAHI said the decision came late because 
postal charges and the tolls for Tokyo expressways have already 
been increased, but said it supports the decision. It urged 
public service companies to work on a drastic restructuring 
during the time the freeze is in effect. 
  The MAINICHI SHIMBUN said it understands the decision by 
Hata 
although his aim is not so clear, and said not many citizens 
object to it. But the MAINICHI warned Hata that consumers will 
be very angry if public service charges are raised by a margin 
higher than the current increase plans after the freeze ends. 

</TEXT>

