<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reactions to Hikes in Public Utility Charges Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reactions to Hikes in Public Utility Charges Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    NTT, Others Embarrassed by Freeze </H4>

<F P=102> OW1805122594 Tokyo KYODO in English 1207 GMT 18 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1805122594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 18 KYODO -- An abrupt government 
decision Wednesday [18 May] to freeze hikes of public service 
charges until the year-end came as a surprise to Nippon 
Telegraph and Telephone Corp. (NTT) and other enterprises 
concerned, industry sources said. 
  Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata ordered the freeze and the 
government will ask local authorities to follow suit, Chief 
Cabinet Secretary Hiroshi Kumagai said. 
  NTT, which plans to raise basic telephone charges by an 
average 18 percent, said the company will follow decisions by 
public hearings and an advisory panel at the Posts and 
Telecommunications Ministry. 
  Company officials, however, said they were upset by the 
government's decision, which will have an impact on the 
company's business performance. 
  The nonlife insurance industry also said it was surprised by 
the decision. Takashi Onoda, head of the Marine and Fire 
Insurance Association of Japan, told reporters the industry was 
considerably upset by it. 
  The decision came as nonlife insurers applied to the Finance 
Ministry for approval of their plans to raise fire insurance 
rates, effective July 1. 
  Major nonlife insurance companies said they did not know 
immediately what impact the decision would have on their 
business. 
  Kohei Abe, president of the Federation of Electric Power 
Companies, said member companies will decide whether to revise 
utility charges at their own discretion. 
  The power companies will keep lower rates until September to 
return foreign exchange gains to consumers. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

