<H3> <TI>   Truck Firm Develops Efficient Diesel Engine </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Truck Firm Develops Efficient Diesel Engine </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1905003894 Tokyo KYODO in English 2331 GMT 18 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1905003894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 19 KYODO -- Hino Motors Ltd., a leading 
Japanese truck maker, has developed the world's most efficient 
large-scale diesel engine, a Japanese industrial daily reported 
Thursday [19 May]. 
  The turbocharged, 10000-cc engine is 10 percent more fuel 
efficient than similar large-scale diesel engines without 
sacrificing power and torque, the NIKKEI SANGYO SHIMBUN said. 
  The engine, called P11C, uses pistons made of a new material 
mixed with heat-blocking graphite to raise thermal efficiency, 
in the first application of this new technology, it said. 
  The use of the new material makes it possible to raise 
combustion efficiency to 46 percent from the previous ceiling of 
43 percent for similar engines, the daily said. 
  Hino has used the engine in some of its large-size trucks 
and 
has no plans to sell the engine by itself, it said. 

</TEXT>

