<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Tokyo, Washington Framework Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Tokyo, Washington Framework Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Follow-Up Meeting on Paper Trade </H4>

<F P=102> OW1905120194 Tokyo KYODO in English 1126 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1905120194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 19 KYODO -- Japan and the United States 
held regular consultations Thursday [19 May] in Tokyo on ways to 
improve foreign access to Japan's paper market. 
  The biannual meeting was held to evaluate implementation of 
a 
set of measures both parties agreed during the paper trade talks 
in April 1992. 
  A U.S. official who attended the meeting told reporters that 
the two countries discussed "several areas" of the world's 
second largest paper and paperboard market. But he refused to 
disclose the contents of the talks. 
  The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, only said, 
"we have yet to see results confirming a substantial increase in 
foreign access to the Japanese market." 
  The official said the foreign share of the Japanese paper 
market was only 3.9 percent at the end of 1993, up only 0.2 
percentage point from 1991. The official cited what Washington 
views as "the highly structured distribution system" and 
"discriminatory corporate purchasing practices" as major factors 
to thwart smooth American penetration of the 32 billion dollar 
market. 
  Due to these "systemic obstacles, persistent and strong 
efforts by the world-class competitor" in other markets have not 
been rewarded, the official said. 

</TEXT>

