<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Overseas Training for Public Officials Raised </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Overseas Training for Public Officials Raised </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1805014894 Seoul YONHAP in English 0116 GMT 18 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1805014894 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, May 18 (YONHAP) -- The government, as part of 
its campaign to boost the country's competitiveness, has decided 
to increase overseas training opportunities for public officials 
and widen the training scope of government agencies, 
international organizations and research institutes. 
  Two hundred public officials will be trained abroad next 
year, up 30 percent from 150, according to the 1995 state-funded 
training program for civil servants released by the Government 
Administration Ministry Tuesday. 
  Noting overseas training so far was limited to academic 
studies and getting degrees, public officials will also be sent 
to foreign government agencies, international organizations, and 
think tanks for field studies with a view to raising their 
practical abilities to handle external negotiations. 
  Training will no longer be restricted to advanced countries. 
Eighty officials will be trained at English-speaking countries; 
35 in non-English speaking countries like Japan, Germany, and 
France; 35 in other areas, and 50 in international organizations 
and research institutes. 
  Public officials in good standing and recommended by their 
agencies will be chosen by the end of October after testing 
their language ability, a Ministry official said. 
  On returning from their overseas training, officials have to 
serve two to three years in related posts, he said. 

</TEXT>

