<F P=101> Singapore </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Zealand's Bolger on Human Rights Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    New Zealand's Bolger on Human Rights Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1905074394 Melbourne Radio Australia in English 0500 GMT 
19 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1905074394 </F>
<F P=104>  Melbourne Radio Australia </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] New Zealand's prime minister, Jim Bolger, says the 
strength of Asian economies is helping them resist pressures 
from the West on human rights issues. Speaking in Singapore, 
Mr. Bolger said Asian countries were now able to say with some 
firmness that their approach to human rights was as valid as 
that of anybody else. He said countries in Asia were better able 
to deal with such issues now that everyone wanted to trade with 
them. 
  Early this week, Mr. Bolger came under criticism in New 
Zealand for endorsing Indonesian rule in East Timor despite 
Western concerns over human rights there. 

</TEXT>

