<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government To Offer Training to DPRK Loggers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government To Offer Training to DPRK Loggers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1905092394 Seoul YONHAP in English 0822 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1905092394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, May 19 (YONHAP) -- The government plans to 
give the five North Korean loggers who arrived Wednesday the 
opportunity to attend public vocational training centers here 
according to their goals, aptitude and ability, a senior 
government official said Thursday. 
  The loggers, the first allowed to resettle here through 
consultations between South Korea and the Commonwealth of 
Independent States, will receive social adaption education first 
for one or two months before entering vocational training 
institutes. 
  The government, however, is studying whether to place them 
in 
existing classes at the centers or educate them separately, 
according to the official. 
  The five North Koreans, who escaped from Pyongyang-run 
logging camps in Siberia, arrived here Wednesday afternoon via a 
third country. It is the first time that the Seoul government 
has allowed North Korean loggers to resettle here through lawful 
means. 
  In preparation for the increase in those wanting to come 
here 
after escaping from the Siberian logging camps or North Korean 
territory, the government is studying formation of a "special 
training team" to deal exclusively with North Koreans. 
  But if they want to receive higher education, the government 
will examine how to enable them to enter colleges or 
universities, the official said. 
  The government has tentatively decided to help the North 
Koreans find jobs after they finish vocational training, and 
will give them 10 million won (about 12,407 U.S. dollars) each 
in support for their resettlement. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

