<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Impact of Proposed Textile Import Curb Noted </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Impact of Proposed Textile Import Curb Noted </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1905061294 Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 18 May 94 
Morning Edition p 8--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1905061294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Yoshiyuki Itsumi, Economic News Department] </F>
  [Text] The decision by the Ministry of International Trade 
and Industry [MITI] to invoke safeguards under the MFA 
[Multi-Fiber Arrangement] will be a "double-edged sword" for 
this ministry which supposedly upholds free trade. The present 
decision represents a major step toward the actual introduction 
of safeguards. Behind this is the fact that the textile 
industry is seriously distressed by the deluge of imports, and 
the shift in Japanese trade policy in line with efforts to lay 
down economic rules in preparation for the inauguration of the 
World Trade Organization (WTO). 
  However, import curbs may result in further inflation of the 
current account surplus, and foreign countries are certain to 
apply stronger pressure on Japan to reduce its surplus 
drastically. 
  The Western countries have implemented import curbs under 
the 
MFA for more than 20 years. The United States imposes 
restrictions on 80 percent of its imported textile items, while 
the European Union (EU) regulates 50 percent of these products. 
  In contrast, Japan, in consideration of its export products 
creating economic frictions overseas, had not even considered 
conditions for invoking MFA safeguards. 
  In the past, when the Japanese textile industry filed 
dumping 
charges and complained about their difficult position, MITI has 
always dealt with the issue in an ambiguous manner, engaging in 
behind-the-scenes contacts with the trading partners concerned, 
and asking them to implement actual self-restraint in exports. 
  However, with the prospective establishment of the WTO, 
unilateral self-restraint in exports will be banned in principle 
as being a "gray measure." Japan, therefore, recently abolished 
its voluntary restriction on passenger car exports to the United 
States by the end of 31 March. 
  If export restrictions are to be imposed on textile 
products, 
Japan will now have to negotiate with its trading partners, and 
reach a decision based on MFA rules. 
  Already this spring China sent a letter to the minister of 
international trade and industry saying: "In consideration of 
the rapid increase in exports to Japan, we are studying 
appropriate measures," thus indicating it is considering 
voluntary export restrictions. Tough negotiations will now have 
to be conducted to coordinate this with MFA rules. 
  Steps being taken by the textile industry in relation to 
import curbs are also being noted for their effect on efforts to 
determine future policy in this industry which has lost its 
competitiveness. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-53519 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas098__a94011" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-098-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  18 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Private Sector, Government Clash on Deregulation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Private Sector, Government Clash on Deregulation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2005022694 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 18 May 
94 Evening Edition p 3--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2005022694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Private-sector representatives and government 
officials clashed hard over the deregulation issue at a meeting 
of the "Working Group on Import Promotion, Improvement of Market 
Access, and Distribution" of the government's Administrative 
Reform Promotion Headquarters (headed by Prime Minister Tsutomu 
Hata) in the prime minister's office on the morning of 18 May. 
The meeting showed very clearly that the private sector wants 
deregulation to be carried out while the bureaucrats want to 
resist it. 
  In the meeting, the private-sector representatives openly 
complained to ministry bureau directors general: "As long as 
government offices act this way, it will be extremely difficult 
to achieve any significant results in deregulation that would be 
acceptable both at home and abroad." 
  The government offices' position in trying to defend vested 
rights showed up so clearly that the people around the prime 
minister were alarmed, saying: "This way, we can never get any 
significant plan adopted by the end of June." 
  The meeting of the day saw five private-sector members of 
the 
group, which included Professor Tajima of Gakushuin University, 
exchange views with director general-level officials from the 
Ministries of Finance, International Trade and Industry, and 
Transport on topics of controls on commodity distribution, 
specifications and permits, and import procedures. It began 
with explanations by government officials on the present 
conditions of regulation and on the reasons for them. Some of 
the officials said: "We will take positive actions [for 
deregulation]"; but most of them showed a negative stand, 
insisting, "Under the given conditions, we cannot decide for 
deregulation." 
  The private-sector group members reacted strongly against 
the 
position of the offices resisting deregulation, some saying, "It 
is truly regrettable that there is no change in the government 
offices' strong attitude toward defending [regulation]. Others 
said: "The economy should be free of control in principle. You 
must change the attitude of defending regulation, citing Japan's 
special circumstances as the reason." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

