<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dailies Comment on South's Response on POW's </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Dailies Comment on South's Response on POW's </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2005104894 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1020 GMT 20 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2005104894 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Far-Fetched Argument for Sinister Purpose" -- KCNA </F>
headline] 
  [Text] Pyongyang, May 20 (KCNA) -- The North side in recent 
telephone messages respectfully requested the South Korean Red 
Cross to immediately send back to the North Kim In-so and Ham 
Se-hwan, prisoners of war and unconverted long-term prisoners, 
and take measures to allow the children of Kim Pyong-chu, an 
unconverted prisoner who died a few years ago, including the 
eldest daughter Kim Chi-hyon suffering from a serious disease, 
to come to the North to receive medical treatment and be 
protected in their livelihood. 
  The South side, however, has taken no positive measure for 
the repatriation of Kim In-so and Ham Se-hwan, arguing that they 
do not belong to the category of prisoners of war, and blindly 
turns down the request as regards Kim Chi-hyon. 
  It is self-evident that this is a far-fetched argument for a 
sinister purpose, directed by the South Korean authorities 
behind the scene, says NODONG SINMUN in a commentary today. 
  The news analyst says: 
  The argument that Kim In-so and Ham Se-hwan do not fall 
under 
the category of prisoners of war is a sheer distortion of fact. 
They are prisoners of war who were arrested by a warring party 
while active as guerrillas (militiamen) during the last war. 
The South side's argument is a violation of international law 
on humanitarianism and a far-fetched one. 
  What the South side argues about "acquirement of 
nationality" 
is also absurd. Kim In-so and Ham Se-hwan have long since 
wished to return to the North and asked International Red Cross 
organisations to help them in their repatriation. It is 
unreasonable to try to keep them in South Korea for the reason 
of their "acquirement of (South Korean) nationality." 
  Kim In-so and Ham Se-hwan are not "killers of innocent 
people" as described by the South side but patriots who fought 
with arms in hand against foreign aggressors and the traitors of 
South Korea who plunged the innocent people into the scourge of 
war. 
  The South side is rejecting our hand of relief while failing 
to look after sick Kim Chi-hyon and give her medical treatment. 
  This is an act which can be done only by those devoid of 
humanism and national conscience. 
  Either in view of the requirement of international law or in 
view of the Red Cross idea of humanitarianism, it is only too 
natural that the prisoners of war should be repatriated and 
fellow countrymen suffering from poverty and illness be rescued. 
The South side must send them to the North as soon as possible. 
  A MINJU CHOSON analyst demands that the South Korean Red 
Cross meet the North's just demand with the original attitude of 
Red Cross. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

