<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Joins Economic Embargo Against Haiti </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Joins Economic Embargo Against Haiti </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2005011694 Tokyo KYODO in English 0044 GMT 20 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2005011694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 20 KYODO -- Japan declared Friday [20 
May] it will join an international economic embargo against 
Haiti to help oust its military government from power and 
restore civilian rule. 
  Japan will stop loans and investment to Haiti's military 
authorities in line with U.N. Security Council Resolution 917, 
adopted on May 6, Foreign Ministry officials said. 
  The Japanese Government has already banned flights between 
Japan and Haiti except for regular passenger flights, and has 
also taken measures to prevent Haiti military leaders from 
entering Japan, under the U.N. sanctions, it said. 
  Tokyo will also abide by a trade embargo against the 
Caribbean state which takes effect at Saturday midnight, it said. 
  Foreign Ministry spokesman Terusuke Terada said in a 
statement that Japan strongly hopes leaders of the Haiti 
military will take immediate steps to restore democracy. 
  The Security Council unanimously voted on May 6 to tighten 
sanctions against Haiti's military rulers to force them to allow 
the return of exiled President Jean-Bertrand Aristide and 
restore democracy. 
  The resolution calls for banning entry of Haiti military 
leaders into all U.N. member countries, and embargoes exports to 
Haiti except for medical goods and food. 
  It also recommends U.N. member countries to ensure that the 
Haiti military and its leaders cannot use their funds and 
financial resources. 
  The Haiti Army ousted Aristide, Haiti's first democratically 
elected president, in a coup in September 1991. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

