<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Stopgap Supplemental Budget </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Stopgap Supplemental Budget </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Soka Gakkai Issue Stalls Session </H4>

<F P=102> OW1905143694 Tokyo KYODO in English 1415 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1905143694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 19, KYODO -- The House of Councillors 
Budget Committee failed Thursday [19 May] to discuss a stopgap 
supplementary budget for fiscal 1994 over an opposition demand 
to summon a former attorney to a Buddhist lay group linked to 
Komeito, a core party in the ruling coalition. 
  The main opposition Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) demanded 
that Masatomo Yamazaki, former attorney to Soka Gakkai, be 
summoned as an unsworn witness in connection with his alleged 
attempt to tap a telephone line at the House of Japanese 
Communist Party Chairman Kenji Miyamoto. 
  Soka Gakkai is the primary support base for Komeito and 
their 
ties have often become the focus of disputes over the separation 
of religion and politics stipulated in the Constitution. 
  The coalition urged the LDP to attend the committee session 
on Friday to deliberate the 10.89 trillion yen stopgap 
supplementary budget, which will extend for 40 days an original 
50-day provisional budget worth 11.05 trillion yen that expires 
Friday. 
  The LDP, however, declined because the coalition rejected 
its 
demand, parliamentary sources said. 
  The more powerful House of Representatives approved the 
stopgap supplementary budget on Wednesday. 
  The rare supplement to a provisional budget, the first since 
fiscal 1990, followed the continued political turmoil involving 
the resignation of Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa and the 
selection as premier of Tsutomu Hata. 
  Diet deliberations for the 73.08 trillion yen full budget 
for 
the 1994 fiscal year finally started Tuesday. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

