<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Stopgap Supplemental Budget </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Stopgap Supplemental Budget </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Upper House Passes Budget </H4>

<F P=102> OW2005105594 Tokyo KYODO in English 1028 GMT 20 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2005105594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 20 KYODO -- An unusual supplement to an 
earlier stopgap budget nearing expiration cleared the last 
parliamentary hurdle to become a law Friday upon approval from 
the House of Councillors. 
  The plenary session of the upper house of the Japanese 
parliament passed the 10.89 trillion yen supplement to extend 
for 40 days an earlier 50-day provisional budget worth 11.05 
trillion yen. 
  The revised stopgap budget, totaling 21.94 trillion yen, 
will 
expire June 29, when the current Diet session ends. 
  The rare revision of a stopgap budget -- the first since 
fiscal 1990 -- was necessitated by the political confusion 
following the abrupt resignation of former Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa and the selection of Tsutomu Hata as his 
successor. 
  The political turmoil had long stalled Diet deliberations on 
the 73.08 trillion yen full budget for fiscal 1994, which 
started April 1, until Tuesday when budgetary debates finally 
began. 
  The chances for quick passage of the full budget, however, 
are viewed as slim because the Hata government holds only a 
minority in the Diet. 
  The revised interim budget earmarks as little as possible 
for 
the running of administrative bodies, while boosting outlays for 
public works projects. 
  Revised outlays for administrative expenses are set at 25 
percent of the full budget, up from 14 percent in the initial 
stopgap budget. 
  Public works got an additional 1.07 trillion yen, bringing 
the total so far to 3.84 trillion yen, about three-sevenths of 
such investments envisaged under the full budget. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

