<H3> <TI>   Reports Concerning Public Utility Rate Continue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reports Concerning Public Utility Rate Continue </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Transport Minister Denies Future Hike </H4>

<F P=102> OW2005044394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0400 GMT 20 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2005044394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 20 KYODO -- Transport Minister Nobuaki 
Futami denied Friday [20 May] that transportation charges will 
be raised sharply next January after the freeze on hikes in 
public charges this year comes to an end. 
  "The ministry won't be adding anything extra onto the rises 
that were withheld this year," Futami said, dismissing 
speculation that expressway tolls and taxi fares could jump when 
the freeze ends. 
  He said the hikes could be delayed from the planned Jan. 1 
for political reasons, and that there could be another freeze if 
the economy still looks bad at that time. 
  "A lifting of the freeze depends on an economic recovery. If 
the situation looks serious, we will be giving the matter 
further consideration," he said. 
  The minister expressed caution toward exempting the fares of 
small regional taxi companies from the hike freeze this year. 
  "People could be put off from using taxis, (if such 
companies 
are allowed to raise their fares)," he said. 

</TEXT>

