<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reports Concerning Public Utility Rate Continue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reports Concerning Public Utility Rate Continue </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Minister Reviews Utility Rate Fixing </H4>

<F P=102> OW2005041194 Tokyo KYODO in English 0325 GMT 20 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2005041194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 20 KYODO -- International Trade and 
Industry Minister Eijiro Hata on Friday [20 May] called for an 
overall review of the methods for setting public service 
charges, particularly highway tolls. 
  The proposal was made in connection with the government's 
latest decision to uniformly freeze proposed hikes in public 
service rates until the end of the year in easing the burdens on 
a recession-hit private sector. 
  Speaking to reporters, Hata said many cabinet ministers 
agreed earlier in the day on the need for a "thorough and 
drastic review" of the current rate-fixing system. 
  Hata especially criticized "a pool system" used to calculate 
highway tolls as a mechanism that always works toward a rate 
hike. 
  He cited the use of the government's fiscal investment and 
loan fund as one option in replacing the pool system in which 
funds collected by drivers finance new highway construction. 
  The government announced Wednesday it will suspend rates for 
services such as telephones, rents on government-owned houses 
and public transportation. The plan was approved by Friday's 
cabinet meeting. 
  On utility charges, Hata said the issue should be separated 
from charges subject to the latest rate hike freeze. Rates on 
gas and electricity were cut last November as part of efforts to 
pass on to consumers the companies' windfall profits from the 
yen's appreciation against the dollar. The companies said the 
cuts would be effective until the end of September this year. 
  What to do after September is a matter to be handled by the 
industries concerned after taking into account various economic 
factors like crude oil prices and exchange rates, Hata said. 
  On the growing difficulty of female college graduates to 
find 
jobs, with many companies refusing to hire women, citing the 
recession, the trade minister said he will ask the business 
community to "refrain from hesitating" to recruit such students. 
The tendency, if covered by the overseas media, would undermine 
the reputation of Japanese corporations, Hata said. He said he 
will make the request when he meets leaders of the Federation of 
Economic Organizations (Keidanren) next Tuesday. 
  Turning to the ongoing Japan-U.S. informal trade talks in 
Washington, Hata said he has yet to receive any information 
about the meeting. The two countries began subcabinet-level 
talks Thursday in a bid to find common ground for resuming the 
stalled negotiations on a new bilateral trade framework. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-53563 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas098_a_94018" </HT>


<HEADER>
