<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reports Concerning Public Utility Rate Continue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reports Concerning Public Utility Rate Continue </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    EPA Director Cited </H4>

<F P=102> OW2005024394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0222 GMT 20 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2005024394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 20 KYODO -- The government's freeze on 
public service charge hikes was "politically necessary," 
economic planning chief Yoshio Terasawa said Friday [20 May], 
but he expressed concern about the move's across-the-board 
nature. 
  Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata had to order the freeze to 
bolster consumer psychology and help the economy, the director 
general of the Economic Planning Agency (EPA) told a regular 
press conference after a morning cabinet endorsed the freeze. 
  "I think the very fact that it is across-the-board is 
meaningful" for beleaguered consumers, Terasawa said. But he 
said he wants to "respect" the EPA's position that hikes in 
public service charges should be decided case by case. 
  He said the move will have little effect on overall prices, 
which are quite stable in Japan's still-sluggish economy, noting 
that the EPA wants some prices to fall, to reduce disparities 
with overseas prices. But he said the freeze "avoids the 
negative effect" of more increases. 
  In his abrupt decision Wednesday, Hata said the government 
must show the people it is taking the same bitter cost-cutting 
medicine as private enterprises in their restructuring efforts. 
But the move to freeze for the rest of the year a vast array of 
rate hikes needing government approval, and a request to local 
governments to do the same, angered Japan's bureaucracy. Public 
opposition by Vice Finance Minister Jiro Saito was labeled a 
bureaucratic "coup d'etat" by one newspaper Friday. 
  Some cabinet members called at the morning's meeting for a 
drastic overhaul of the system for setting public service 
charges, such as highway tolls, utility rates and transportation 
fares, Terasawa said. 

</TEXT>

