<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 20 KYODO -- Prosecutors demanded Friday 
[20 May] former Chief Cabinet Secretary Takao Fujinami be 
sentenced to three and half years in prison for allegedly taking 
bribes in a shares-for-favor scandal involving Tokyo-based job 
information firm Recruit Co. 
  The Tokyo District Court is expected to hand down a ruling 
by 
the end of the year after Fujinami, 61, and his lawyers deliver 
their final submissions July 14, court officials said. 
  He is the first suspect from within the political circle to 
face a ruling in the series of Recruit scandals that jolted 
Japanese politics in the late 1980s. 
  Fujinami was charged with receiving 10,000 unlisted shares 
and 20 million yen in checks from Recruit in exchange for 
political favors. 

