<DOCNO> FBIS4-53573 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas098_a_94028" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-098 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  20 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   BOJ Sees No `Clear' Signs of Impending Recovery </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    BOJ Sees No `Clear' Signs of Impending Recovery </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2005111394 Tokyo KYODO in English 1046 GMT 20 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2005111394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 20 KYODO -- The economy has yet to show 
that it is about to recover but the long economic slump is not 
worsening, the Bank of Japan (BOJ) said Friday [20 May]. 
  "Japan's economic growth appears to have stopped weakening," 
the BOJ said in its monthly economic review, using almost the 
same words as a month ago. "However, there are no clear 
indications of imminent recovery." 
  Personal consumption, a main engine of growth, "is picking 
up 
gradually," while housing and public-sector investment are 
strong, but corporate capital spending is still falling, the 
report says. 
  Job growth remains slow, the central bank said, but it noted 
a halt to the falling ratio of job offers to seekers. 
  Money supply growth remains low due to weak lending by 
banks, 
the report asserts, saying rises in March and April to the top 
of the BOJ's forecast range resulted from "portfolio shifts 
between money and other financial assets" not counted in the 
money supply. 
  On inflation, it says domestic wholesale prices are falling 
on weak demand and cheaper imports, service prices are stable 
and consumer price increases remain low. 
  Industrial production "has virtually stopped decreasing," 
the 
central bank said, although it noted that the trade ministry 
expects declines in April and May in the wake of stepped-up 
spending before the end of the fiscal year. 
  Capital spending continues to fall among manufacturers -- 
except for such bright spots as semiconductors, liquid crystal 
displays and cellular telephones -- and is stagnant among 
nonmanufacturers, the report says. 
  It notes recent rises in Japan's trade surplus but says the 
current-account surplus "has peaked" due to "larger deficits in 
invisible and transfer accounts." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

