Daily Report 
<DATE1>  20 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Industrial Production Increases 4.6% in Mar </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Industrial Production Increases 4.6% in Mar </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2005064394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0631 GMT 20 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2005064394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 20 KYODO -- Japan's industrial 
production in March increased 4.6 percent from the preceding 
month, the Ministry of International Trade and Industry (MITI) 
said in a revised report Friday [20 May]. 
  The seasonally adjusted production index for the mining and 
manufacturing sectors came to 92.7 against a base of 100 for 
1990. The growth compares with a 3.3 percent rise in a 
preliminary report released in late February, MITI said. 
  The shipment index, given as 95.3, increased 4.8 percent 
from 
February, revised upward from a 3.9 percent rise in the 
preliminary report. 
  The inventory index, at 105.4, fell 1.1 percent against a 
preliminary 0.8 percent drop. 
  The index of the inventory-to-sales ratio, at 112.7, 
declined 
5.3 percent compared with a 4.5 percent fall in the earlier 
report. 
  With the latest statistics, Japan's industrial output has 
scored ups and downs alternately in the past eight months. 
Before adjustments, March industrial production decreased a 
revised 2.1 percent from a year earlier, extending a record 
string of year-to-year declines to 30 months. Unadjusted 
shipments fell a revised 2.6 percent from a year before and 
unadjusted inventories a revised 3.4 percent. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

