<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Released Annual Earnings Indicate Recession </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Released Annual Earnings Indicate Recession </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2005015894 Tokyo KYODO in English 0109 GMT 20 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2005015894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 20 KYODO -- Japan's annual corporate 
earnings season set in Friday [20 May], with the number of 
companies releasing their earnings for the latest business year 
ended March 31 peaking at around 250. 
  The companies make up about 20 percent of Japanese companies 
closing their books on March 31. 
  The so-called Kabutocho Press Club within the Tokyo Stock 
Exchange was packed like a morning commuter train with reporters 
and corporate financial officers for earnings announcements. 
  The effects of the prolonged recession were reflected in the 
results, with many companies reporting, "sales went down because 
of the recession," or "the high yen cut into profits." 
  Until now, some 350 companies have announced their results 
for their latest business year, showing a decline of some 6 
percent in combined sales and a fall of some 14 percent in 
combined pretax profits from year-earlier levels. 
  "If steel and auto companies which announce their results 
next week are added up, pretax profits will go down further, 
probably by more than 20 percent," an economist at a private 
think tank said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

