<F P=100> AUSTRALIASIA </F>
<F P=101> Australia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Reveals Stance on Rwanda Situation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Reveals Stance on Rwanda Situation </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Government Position Clarified </H4>

<F P=102> BK2005060494 Melbourne Radio Australia in English 0500 GMT 
20 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2005060494 </F>
<F P=104>  Melbourne Radio Australia </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Australian Government has denied a United 
Nations statement that Australia has agreed to commit troops to 
a UN peacekeeping force in Rwanda. A UN spokesman had named 
nine countries, including Australia, what he said would send 
infantry troops to join the UN force. But an Australian 
spokesman said that while the government has committed in 
principle to a peacekeeping mission to Rwanda, it had not 
decided what form its involvement would take. He said Australia 
is awaiting an assessment of the Rwandan situation by a UN 
observer team. The UN plans to send 5,500 troops to Rwanda 
where hundreds of thousands of people are reported to have died 
in ethic violence. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

