<F P=100> AUSTRALIASIA </F>
<F P=101> Vanuatu </F>
<H3> <TI>   Former NUP Ministers Form New Political Party </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Former NUP Ministers Form New Political Party </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1905073794 Melbourne Radio Australia in English 0500 GMT 
19 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1905073794 </F>
<F P=104>  Melbourne Radio Australia </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A new political party is being formed in Vanuatu by 
a breakaway faction of the National United Party [NUP] of former 
prime minister Father Walter Lini. The People's Democratic 
Party is led by three government ministers who were expelled 
from the United Party last week. They are Deputy Prime Minister 
Sethy Regenvanu, Health Minister Edward Tabisari, and 
Communications Minister Cecil Sinker. The three make up the 
junior partner in the coalition government of the Union of 
Moderate Parties. They have been joined by the former 
agriculture minister, Oneyn Tahi, who accused the NUP of being 
dictatorial when he resigned from the party. 
  Mr. Regenvanu said in launching the new party last night 
that 
the objective of the People's Democratic Party would be a fair 
sharing of resources to the advancement of Vanuatu and its 
people. 

</TEXT>

