<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-098 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  20 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Philippines </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Colonel's Killers Said Covered by Amnesty </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Colonel's Killers Said Covered by Amnesty </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2005103294 Quezon City PTV-4 Television Network in Tagalog 
0500 GMT 20 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2005103294 </F>
<F P=104>  Quezon City PTV-4 Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Tagalog </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Major General Alfredo Filler, Armed Forces of the 
Philippines [AFP] vice chief of staff, stressed that the members 
of the Alex Boncayao Brigade involved in the killing of U.S. 
Colonel James Rowe are covered by the government's amnesty 
program. Filler said that the killers were captured and 
punished. They, however, still have the right to apply for the 
amnesty program. 
  It will be recalled that the U.S. Government objected to the 
granting of amnesty to the three New People's Army rebels who 
killed Rowe while on his way to JUSMAG [Joint United States 
Military Advisory and Planning Group] in Quezon City during the 
latter part of 1980. 
  According to Filler, the Philippines will not be violating 
the diplomatic agreement which it signed wherein the government 
will give protection to American nationals in the country. 
Filler clarified that the agreement does not stipulate the 
banning of parole or amnesty. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

